\par {\b Boot Bonus}
\par The boot bonus allows a player to kick bombs of their own colour.  To kick a bomb a player simply runs into it.  A kicked bomb will move until it hits an obstacle, at which point it will explode. 
\par 
\par 
\par {\cs16\b\fs24\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s15\widctlpar \f4\fs20\lang2057 {\cs16\super #} megariot}}{\b\fs24  Mega-Riot}
\par Mega riot is enforced after the number of seconds specified in the options box.  In Mega-riot mode,  silver bombs will start to appear randomly in the maze.
\par 
\par {\cs16\b\fs24\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s15\widctlpar \f4\fs20\lang2057 {\cs16\super #} panel}}{\b\fs24  Game Panel}
\par To the right of the maze, the game panel shows the bonus status of each of the players and how many games that each player has won in the current match.  Also shown is the time remaining until Mega-riot sets in and the speed at which the game is running. 
 
\par 
\par {\cs16\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s15\widctlpar \f4\fs20\lang2057 {\cs16\super #} speed}} 
The game speed is shown as a percentage.  If the speed is consistently below about 85% then it may help to close some other applications.   Although undesirable, turning of the sound will speed the game up on slower machines if you notice a significant de
lay when bombs explode.  
\par 
\par The \lquote Run as fast as possible\rquote  option will cause the game to ignore its game cycle rate of 17 cycles per second.  On the 486DX100 that the game was written on this results in speeds as high as 230%.  If the game speed goes higher t
han 999% then there will be a display problem, however, if you can play the game at these speeds you should not be concerning yourself with such trivialities.
\par 
\par {\cs16\b\fs24\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s15\widctlpar \f4\fs20\lang2057 {\cs16\super #} ai}}{\b\fs24  Computer Players
\par }
The computer players have varying degrees of artificial stupidity.  Each computer player will play very well defensively; they will avoid bombs whenever possible and will not drop bombs that trap themselves.   The differences appear in their offensive pla
y.  The weakest form of offensive play is to drop bombs randomly without 
attempting to destroy the other players or to obtain bonuses.  The highest AI level is to go for bonuses and to actively attempt to destroy the other players.  The differences should be noticeable in an all-computer match running for a few dozen games.

\par 
\par {\cs16\b\fs24\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s15\widctlpar \f4\fs20\lang2057 {\cs16\super #} mazes}}{\b\fs24  The Mazes}
\par The mazes are stored in the ASCII file BOMBMAZE.TXT.  The key is:
\par 
\par {\f3 I - Wall
\par C - Crate (bonus)
\par . - Floor
\par E - Explosive
\par R - Red Starting Position
\par B - Blue Starting Position
\par G - Green Starting Position
\par P - Purple Starting Position
\par } 
\par Mazes are stored as 13 squares across and 11 squares down.  There are eight mazes and the program expects to find a space between each maze.  A starting position is provided for each player.  
\par 
\par The mazes provided are designed so that there are no 2x2 patterns of only floor tiles.  This is because the bombs only explode directly horizontally and directly vertically.  This rule is not enforced by the program when reading a maze.
\par 
